const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---
<Post title="The 583-Dimensional Input Vector" date="April 2026" activeTab="deep-dive">
  <p>
    The neural network needs to see the game state as a fixed-size numeric vector.
    Translating a complex card game state — with variable-length hands, multiple
    enemies, and dozens of status effects — into 583 numbers is one of the core
    engineering challenges of this project.
  </p>

  <div class="hero-img">
    <img src={`${base}screenshots/combat1.png`} alt="STS2 combat state" />
  </div>

  <h2>Vector Breakdown</h2>
  <p>The 583 dimensions break down into six groups:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>18 player scalars</strong> — HP, block, energy, turn number, debuffs, action counters</li>
    <li><strong>270 hand card features</strong> — 10 slots x (16d learned embedding + 11 extras like cost, type, keywords)</li>
    <li><strong>252 enemy features</strong> — 6 slots x (16d learned embedding + 17 scalars + 4 intent flags + power slots)</li>
    <li><strong>24 pile features</strong> — Draw, discard, and exhaust piles, each mean-pooled to 8d</li>
    <li><strong>10 relic features</strong> — All relics mean-pooled (8d embedding + counter + active flag)</li>
    <li><strong>9 power features</strong> — Active player powers mean-pooled (8d embedding + amount)</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Learned Embeddings</h2>
  <p>
    Card names, enemy types, relics, and powers are represented as learned embeddings
    rather than one-hot vectors. Each ID maps to a vocabulary index, which looks up a
    dense vector from an <code>nn.Embedding</code> layer. These embeddings are trained
    end-to-end with the policy — the network learns its own representation of what
    each card or enemy "means."
  </p>
  <p>
    This is critical because the vocabulary grows as training progresses through
    curriculum stages. New cards and enemies get new embedding rows, initialized
    randomly, and the network learns to use them.
  </p>

  <h2>Normalization</h2>
  <p>
    All numeric values are normalized to roughly [0, 1] or [-1, 1]. HP is divided by
    max HP. Debuff stacks are divided by observed game maximums (e.g. poison / 200,
    strength / 300). This keeps the input scale consistent so the network doesn't
    overweight large raw numbers.
  </p>

